## 📁 FILE-BY-FILE EXPLANATION

### 1. [pom.xml](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/pom.xml) — The Shopping List

**What it is:** Maven build file — tells Java what libraries to download.

**Key dependencies:**
| Dependency | Why We Need It |
|---|---|
| `spring-boot-starter-web` | Gives us controllers, RestTemplate, embedded Tomcat server |
| `lombok` | Generates getters/setters/constructors automatically (less typing) |
| `jackson-databind` | Converts JSON ↔ Java objects automatically |

**Beginner tip:** When you write `@Data` on a class, Lombok auto-generates `getXxx()`, `setXxx()`, `toString()`, `equals()`, `hashCode()`. Without Lombok, you'd write 50+ lines of boilerplate per model class.

---

### 2. [ShopeeConfig.java](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/config/ShopeeConfig.java) — The Password Vault

```java
public static final long PARTNER_ID = 0L;         // Your Shopee app ID
public static final String PARTNER_KEY = "...";    // Your secret key
public static final long SHOP_ID = 0L;             // Your shop ID
public static final String BASE_URL = "https://partner.test-stable.shopeemobile.com";
```

**Why static fields?** For now, simplicity. Later you'd replace these with `@Value("${shopee.partner-id}")` to read from [application.properties](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/resources/application.properties) or environment variables (more secure).

---

### 3. [ShopeeSignatureUtil.java](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/util/ShopeeSignatureUtil.java) — The Secret Handshake 🤝

**The Problem:** Shopee needs proof that YOU are making the request, not a hacker.

**The Solution:** HMAC-SHA256 — a cryptographic signing algorithm.

**How it works:**
```
You have:  partner_key = "mysecret"
You build: base_string = "12345" + "/api/v2/order/get_order_detail" + "1700000000" + "token123" + "67890"
You compute: HMAC-SHA256("mysecret", base_string) = "a3f5c8d2e1..."
You send:  ?sign=a3f5c8d2e1... (as a URL parameter)
```

Shopee does the same computation on their end. If both signatures match → request is authentic. If someone tries to modify the request, the signatures won't match → request rejected.

**Three types of signatures based on API type:**

| API Type | Base String Components |
|---|---|
| Public | partnerId + path + timestamp |
| Shop | partnerId + path + timestamp + accessToken + shopId |
| Merchant | partnerId + path + timestamp + accessToken + merchantId |

---

### 4. [ShopeeAuthService.java](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/auth/ShopeeAuthService.java) — The Token Manager 🔑

**The Problem:** You can't just send your password with every request. That's insecure.

**The Solution:** OAuth 2.0 — get a temporary "pass" (token) that expires.

**The Flow:**
```
STEP 1: Seller clicks "Authorize" on Shopee → You get an auth_code
STEP 2: You exchange auth_code for → access_token (4hrs) + refresh_token (30 days)
STEP 3: Use access_token for API calls
STEP 4: When access_token expires → use refresh_token to get a new one
STEP 5: When refresh_token expires → seller must re-authorize
```

**Key methods:**
```java
getAccessToken(authCode, shopId)     // Step 2: first-time token exchange
refreshAccessToken(shopId)           // Step 4: automatic renewal
ensureValidAccessToken(shopId)       // Smart: returns cached token OR refreshes
```

---

### 5. [TokenCacheManager.java](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/auth/TokenCacheManager.java) — The Memory 🧠

**The Problem:** Getting a new token for EVERY API call is wasteful (extra network call each time).

**The Solution:** Cache tokens in memory.

```java
ConcurrentHashMap<Long, ShopeeTokenInfo> tokenCache  // shopId → token
```

**How it works:**
```
API call needed → Is there a cached token? 
  ├── YES → Is it expired?
  │     ├── NO → Use it! ✅ (fast, no network call)
  │     └── YES → Refresh it, cache the new one, use it
  └── NO → Get a new one, cache it, use it
```

**Why `ConcurrentHashMap`?** Thread-safety. If multiple requests come at the same time, they won't corrupt the cache.

---

### 6. [ShopeeWebhookController.java](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/controller/ShopeeWebhookController.java) — The Receptionist 📞

**Only 1 endpoint:** `POST /ims/shopee/events.json`

```java
@PostMapping("/events.json")
public ResponseEntity<String> handleWebhookEvent(@RequestBody ShopeeWebhookRequest request) {
    webhookProcessor.process(request);    // Hand off immediately
    return ResponseEntity.ok("OK");       // Tell Shopee "message received"
}
```

**Why so thin?** Controllers should only:1. Accept input 2. Delegate to service 3. Return output

No logic. No decisions. That's the service's job.

---

### 7. [ShopeeWebhookProcessor.java](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/service/ShopeeWebhookProcessor.java) — The Mail Sorter 📬

**The Problem:** Shopee sends many types of events through ONE endpoint.

**The Solution:** A dispatcher that routes each event to the right handler.

```java
switch (eventType) {
    case "ORDER_STATUS"   → handleOrderEvent(data);
    case "PAYMENT_UPDATE" → handlePaymentEvent(data);
    case "CUSTOMER_JOIN"  → handleCustomerJoinEvent(data);
    default               → handleUnknownEvent(data);  // Future-proof!
}
```

**To add a new event type later:**
1. Add a constant in [ShopeeConstants.java](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/constant/ShopeeConstants.java)
2. Add a `case` + handler method here
3. That's it. No controller changes needed. ✅

---

### 8. [ShopeeService.java](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/service/ShopeeService.java) + [ShopeeServiceImpl.java](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/service/ShopeeServiceImpl.java) — The API Caller 📡

**Interface** (the menu):
```java
List<OrderResponse> getOrderDetails(FetchOrderRequest request);
OrderResponse createOrder(CreateOrderRequest request);
ShipmentResponse updateShipment(UpdateShipmentRequest request);
CancelOrderResponse cancelOrder(CancelOrderRequest request);
```

**Implementation** (the kitchen) — the most complex file. Here's the key pattern:

```
Every API call goes through executeWithRetry():

1. Get valid token (from cache or refresh)
2. Build URL: base_url + api_path + ?partner_id=...&timestamp=...&sign=...&access_token=...&shop_id=...
3. Make HTTP call via RestTemplate
4. If 401 Unauthorized:
   a. Clear cached token
   b. Get fresh token
   c. Retry ONCE
   d. If still fails → throw exception (no infinite loops!)
5. Return the response
```

**Why centralized retry?** Instead of copy-pasting retry logic in every method, it's in ONE place ([executeWithRetry](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/service/ShopeeServiceImpl.java#154-206)). This is the **DRY principle** (Don't Repeat Yourself).

---

### 9. Model Classes (POJOs) — The Data Shapes 📦

**What are they?** Plain Java classes that represent JSON data.

**Example — when Shopee sends this JSON webhook:**
```json
{
  "code": 3,
  "event_type": "ORDER_STATUS",
  "shop_id": 12345,
  "data": { "ordersn": "ABC", "status": "PAID" }
}
```

**Spring/Jackson automatically converts it to:**
```java
ShopeeWebhookRequest request = ...;
request.getCode()       // → 3
request.getEventType()  // → "ORDER_STATUS"
request.getShopId()     // → 12345
request.getData()       // → Map with ordersn, status
```

**No manual JSON parsing!** The `@JsonProperty("order_sn")` annotation tells Jackson which JSON field maps to which Java field.

---

### 10. [ShopeeApiException.java](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/exception/ShopeeApiException.java) + [GlobalExceptionHandler.java](file:///d:/Inventrik%202.0/Project%201/Shopee/src/main/java/com/inventrik/integration/shopee/exception/GlobalExceptionHandler.java) — The Safety Net 🛡️

**Custom exception** carries rich error info:
```java
throw new ShopeeApiException(401, "error_auth", "Token expired", "req-123");
```

**Global handler** catches ALL exceptions and returns structured JSON:
```json
{
  "timestamp": "2026-02-24T00:30:00Z",
  "error": "error_auth",
  "message": "Token expired",
  "httpStatus": 401,
  "requestId": "req-123"
}
```

**Why?** Without this, Spring returns ugly HTML error pages. With this, every error is a clean JSON — perfect for API consumers.

